as it is to suffer once, than to do many times for a friend;
he may do what he will, that will do but what they may.

div.p:
I never desired such Victories, as might serve to conquer, but only restore
the Laws and Liberties of my People, which I saw were extremely oppressed;
together with my Rights, by those men, who were impatient of any just restraint.

Fifthly, I writ a Book against Popery, in Answer to Fisher the Jesuit;
and then the Argument is this; I writ a Book against Popery;
Ergo, I am inclinable to Popery, and laboured to introduce it.

