               To these I may adde Chammo Greenvile of Pughill Cornwall, who
is 657 l. deep in their Books at Haberdashers, and Goldsmiths-hall;
and Thomas Chudley of Aishton Devonshire. 430 l.

In fine, having saved the Plate and Books of Sion-Colledge in London when he was President, having bestowed his own upon the Church to which he owed it (hating to enrich private Families into Pride, with the publick emoluments of the Church, given to Piety) and having led an exact and an exquisite life, 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉
in a conversation so studied, that it was in all things consonant with its self, in most unaffected gravity, wonderful simplicity, and a stern Countenance, proportionable to the vigor and strength of his Soul: 〈 in non-Latin alphabet 〉 : a look that was not one key below his intent, eager, and sprightly minde;
wholly careful of the things he hoped for, and regardless of the things he saw. He died in a good old age, 1662/3.

